{
  "doc_id": "16234",
  "text": "AQP1 serum levels exhibited a temporal profile similar to that of VEGF. It was significantly increased at 2 h after injury and remained elevated at 1 month. In the CNS, AQP1 is mostly expressed by epithelial cells of the choroid plexus; as the major water-transporting protein in choroid plexus, it is involved in CSF production [CITATION_1] . However, AQP1 is also expressed in several nonneural cells including epithelial cells of the lung and peritoneum among others. [CITATION_2] . Chronically elevated serum levels of AQP1 can indicate injury to peripheral organs, such as the lungs or the GI tract; indeed, their roles have been suggested in the peripheral pathomechanism of bTBI [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] .",
